{{Entity Class|Agg=5|Int=3|Dan=4|no=8|Hab=Majority of levels; most notably those abandoned by [[Phenomenon 12|unfortunate circumstances]].}}

==✦ Overview==
{{Blurimage|file=Hound pursuit.gif|caption=Captured video of a Hound within Level 16.}}
Entity 8 (Hounds), are hostile canid entities which inhabit sparsely populated regions of The Backrooms, particularly within damp and derelict levels. Despite exhibiting canid traits, Hounds are genetically similar to humans, sharing multiple biotic attributes, as well as critical thinking and the use of rudimentary tools, among other things. In addition, their unique pelt is sought after by numerous groups due to being one of the only sources of leather in the entire Backrooms.

==✦ Behaviors==
Exhibiting behaviors comparable to that of a wild animal, Hounds are exceptionally aggressive to most life. Being fitted with a sharp row of teeth, they are quickly able to incapacitate prey with their powerful jaw strength. Their claws are typically ineffective in combat, being worn dull as a result of clawing at their own face, even to the point of revealing the surrounding bone. Due to their erratic aggression and isolation within the Backrooms, Hounds tend to run out of energy fairly quickly, which, as a result, leads to a decrease in hunting and foraging among individuals.

Despite their hominid origins, Hounds possess slightly below-human intelligence, being able to remember and mentally map their environment. They also appear to recognize faces and differentiate between species, with research suggesting that Hounds may harbor resentment toward human life in particular. Similar to apes and other less-intelligent primates, they are able to use tools such as sticks and rocks for foraging and self-cleaning, although with limited applications.

Hounds are especially notable for their insatiable appetite — with many specimens adapting to draw energy from a variety of organic and inorganic substances. Whilst attacking prey, they typically resort to tearing off large chunks of flesh as opposed to properly incapacitating their target, aiming to consume as much as possible. Hounds have an acute sense of hearing further amplified from that of canids, being able to hear up to two miles away with ease. A sensitive response to light — positive phototaxis — has been reported in many specimens, with Hounds preferring to stay in areas with light sources, particularly in outside areas.

As a result of the excruciating transformation process, Hounds walk and run with a limp, with many either having permanent mobility issues or being unable to run at all. The sounds that a Hound can make are limited to merely disgruntled barks and whines — as the Hound Virus destroys the entity's speech center during the infection process.

==✦ Biological Makeup==
As mentioned before, Hounds share most biological traits with humans, as the process of interspecies transformation leaves a large portion of their DNA intact. As a result, they also develop canid traits such as excellent hearing and hind legs, which make them unable to stand upright. Hounds have thin, bony limbs and gleaming white eyes which are easily identifiable from a distance in dark areas.

Hounds possess a massive, gaping maw lined with several rows of teeth, used to easily tear into and saw at both flesh and inorganic materials, being able to crack shells and bones with ease. As the hind legs develop into paws upon transformation, they retain their hand structure on the front legs, though with a distinct webbed shape, akin to congenital syndactyly<ref>A birth defect where fingers appear 'webbed' rather than separated.</ref>. Hounds have a long row of black, scraggly hair on their back, making them easily identifiable from a distance and easily differentiable from a human. 

===Egremond Syndrome===
{{Blurimage|file=Hound Virus.jpg|caption='''Egremond Syndrome''' (''Caniscontagione'') sample under a Microscope. Its appearance is notably similar to Rabies.}}
Caniscontagione, commonly known as Egremond Syndrome or the Hound Virus, is a rabies-like neurotropic virus which facilitates rapid DNA mutation and cell growth — transforming affected individuals into Hounds. The disease was coined by Robert J. Egremond, a pharmacist who discovered the pathogen by studying deceased Hound specimens. Symptoms of Egremond Syndrome include:
* ‣ Heavy migraines and lightheadedness;
* ‣ Increased aggression, foaming at the mouth, and other symptoms of rabies;
* ‣ Discoloration around the bite wound, similar to jaundice;
* ‣ Vomiting and stomach cramps;
* ‣ And a mange-like skin disease that covers a large area around the wound.
Egremond Syndrome is a quick-acting disease. Approximately 20-30 minutes after the initial symptoms appear, the infected's body will reconstruct to match that of a Hound. The entire process is visibly and auditorily excruciating, as normal human teeth and nails are painfully pushed out to be replaced by fangs and claws, whereas hands and feet are reconstructed to move exclusively on all-fours. As rapid hair growth occurs all over the body, the eyes will lose their pigmentation — with skin and muscle thinning around the skull and limbs, giving them their signature bony appearance, as rapid cell expansion causes deformities such as bone growths and additional digits in some specimens. 

After around an hour of excruciating transformation, the victim will enter a dazed and aggressive state, with the victim having a surge of initial aggression. During this phase, which lasts around a month, the Hound will be considerably more agile and aggressive than normal specimens, actively seeking out prey as a result. As the infected gradually becomes adjusted to their new life, aggression will stall considerably, though still retaining truculent behaviors. 

As of now, there is no known cure for the Hound Virus.

==✦ Survival Guide==
When faced with a Hound, it is advised that one retains their distance and backs away slowly, as one would with wild animals within [[The Frontrooms]]. If bitten, dousing the wound in [[Object 1|Almond Water]] has been shown to be especially effective in neutralizing the pathogen, though there is only around a five-minute time frame to do so, with bloodletting and electroshock therapy being alternative effective treatments.

If the virus is within an individual's body for over ten minutes, neutralizing the bite victim is the most recommended course of action in such a scenario.

As Hounds have positive phototaxis<ref>Tendency to move towards light.</ref>, turning off lights is one of the best methods to avoid such an encounter. The most efficient method to properly incapacitate a hound is at range, with crossbows and rifles being the most effective.

